F-ck your New Years Resolution. Yeah, really.

New Year Resolutions are like Crocs, Live Love Laugh wall decor, Healthy Coke and Karens: unappealing, irrelevant, ineffective and we’d all be better off if they never existed. 

If you think the last statement is harsh, consider this. Resolutions are a vow to change a behavior immediately and entirely, like some some magical unicorn swoops in at the stroke of midnight with a fresh new motivation to unbox. Sounds legit. 🙄 

The fact is, the majority of our resolutions are too lofty or too vague-lose twenty pounds, read three books a week, be nicer or get organized, for example. It has a similar success rate as dating a person then finding out they clap when the plane lands. Um, zero? Also, anyone who waits until January 1st to become a better person is most likely full of shit and sucks. 

Instead, think in terms of goals. They are much more intention based and hold you accountable because they are finite and specific. Want to lose twenty pounds? How are you going to do it? Break it down into monthly, weekly and daily goals, Want to to save more money for Chanel bags? Same thing. It’s much easier to look at one step than the whole mountain. In the end, your results will be met with far more success. If you do falter time and again, it’s also much easier to get back on track given the specificity. Resolutions just don’t pack enough punch without that.

Goals provide a roadmap to achieve your desired outcome. 

So, fuck your resolutions and set some goals. Follow your heart and your dreams-but use your head.

You can achieve anything if you believe in yourself. And I mean anything. Go get it, I’m pulling for you. HAPPY NEW YEAR AND THIS IS MY FORDT TES TALK OF THE YEAR! 😂💥❤️ #newyearsresolution

I feel very lucky in many ways. But the times I feel the luckiest are when I am treated especially kind by someone unexpectedly-which actually happens quite often. 

Today, I met a woman working in a busy store in Manhattan. In less than ten minutes, I observed several customers come in, ask for their order and leave. Some were a bit nicer than others, but most were just in and out. Fair enough. 
I noticed because when I came in, I smiled and said “Hi, how are you?” I asked if I could shoot a really quick video if I promised not to get in anyone’s way. It would mean so much to me.”
She said yes. If I was manipulating her, I would’ve stopped there. I wasn’t, I was just polite and honest. 

As we waited for her to finish up with some customers I asked her name, where she was from, told her a few words I know in her language and she told me a had gorgeous hair. I asked her name and called her by it. 
Then a couple came in and the girl was a total bitch..I mean, I felt like telling the guy to dump her asap. It was like this odd energy shift took place when they entered. The air became thick with this girl’s presence and the woman behind the counter clearly sensed it, too. At this point we had been waiting to roll, but there had been a steady stream customers, which was fine by me. She was doing me a favor, after all. 
After they paid, she turned to the couple and said, “you can wait outside and I’ll call you in when it’s ready”. 
Then she looked at me with a wink and said, I did that for you, beautiful lady”. 

We did our thing, I thanked her, left a nice tip and she said “You can come back anytime!” as we left. 

Nobody who came through those doors was busier than me. Thirty extra seconds of kindness go a long way. Most people just want to be seen, acknowledged and valued in a very small way. 

I saw her, she saw me. And we all walked away happier. And the bitchy girl is probably still bitching about how she waited outside in the cold for her order.

YOU GET WHAT YOU GIVE ❤️

If Tulum Barbie was a cocktail.

This is a drink I made up and called, La Mar de Menta or Minty Sea because I tweaked a Sea Breeze. I used to drink these a long time ago but now they are so basic and kind of D List..a Sea Breeze is made of vodka, cranberry and grapefruit juice. Exactly, pretty much the basic bitch of cocktails. Facts 😂 

I like tequila for the low carb reasons. Also, even tho it’s not natural, I like to use the low calorie cranberry juice and fresh squeezed grapefruit. Then I add mint, for some freshness and you can even rim the glass with a little simple syrup or pretty sugar. If you’re fancy, you can give those sphere ice cubes a whirl, but the gadget I bought on Amazon to make them sucked, so I never use mine. 

I don’t measure, I’m not a bartender at Chili’s, thankyouverymuch. Plus, most of my friends are drinkers so I’m a bit heavy handed. Pour tequila, cranberry, grapefruit and some mint leaves at the bottom and garnish as you like. You could add a splash of bubbles (don’t waste the good stuff) or even make this as a mocktail and it will feel pretty and summer vibey. Anything would work as a garnish here, it just adds that extra detail. You deserve a pretty drink and NO SOLO CUPS!  It’s not a frat party. 

Clearly, writing recipes isn’t my strong suit, but I do know pretty and this cocktail is PRETTY! 

Enjoy and let me know how you liked it! Salut!

I love dried fruit garnishes in my drinks, it just looks pretty and feels special. If you buy them, it can get pricey and it’s so easy to make at home.
Cut lemons, limes, blood oranges into thin slices and place on parchment lined baking sheet.
Bake for 4-6 hours at 170 degrees, turning every couple of hours. Keep in mind, limes are less juicy so they’ll finish sooner..just keep an eye on them.
Cool and store in an airtight container and they’ll stay fresh for a very long time. And there you go! Easy and stylish. 💥 Salut!

One thing I know for sure is this-most of what you hear about Marseille will be wrong. But if you get out of your tourist comfort zone, you’ll find a vibe unlike anywhere else in France. As the French novelist, Jean-Claude Izzo said so perfectly, “Marseille isn’t a city for tourists. There’s nothing to see. Its beauty can’t be photographed. It can only be shared.”

While I was in midtown Manhattan today, I noticed an increasing number of mentally ill people, but one  in particular stood out to me.
I was standing at the top of the steps of the library scanning the crowd for my mom, my children sitting down next to me, when a woman approached. She was probably in her forties, with a certain beauty, yet with hints of a life marked by hardship. She said, “Don’t  we owe it to ourselves to do our best? To have a great life?” I realized immediately she was off balance. Usually, I get very protective when I’m with my kids. I felt a little uneasy at first, but I let her talk as she blew cigarette smoke in our faces, unknowingly I’m certain. She told me she had children and believed in God, the veracity of which remained uncertain. The truth lay elsewhere—she sought not certainties but a willing and patient listener, if only for a moment. So that’s what we did. As quickly as she appeared, she left. 
It’s easy to get lost in the world, especially for those at risk in a big city. Life is tricky and I really hope she’s ok tonight. 
And I hope you have a nice evening. ♥️
.

If you set a table with plain white dishes, but you have stylish glassware, everything gets elevated. Nobody remembers the dishes, the food maybe. If it’s good.  It nobody talks about the dishes. Glassware is different.
Think of a time  someone handed you a drink in a great glass..you pulled it away from your face, you looked at it and you probably said something about it to whomever you were with-or perhaps just to yourself. You hold it, you feel its weight, it’s up close and then it touches your lips. It’s kind of intimate, if you think about it.
That said, wouldn’t it make sense to focus on the glass you drink from? These are the little details that make a big difference. 

When my son was in the first grade, I volunteered for their Valentina’s Day Party. I piled up a box full of vintage crystal glasses, pretty little dishes and cloth napkins. I got a lot of comments about “how crazy” I was. But I stuck to my plan and watched how DIFFERENTLY these little children behaved. They were quieter, happier and it was clear they felt special. I knew I made the right decision. I wouldn’t have cared if they broke a few, the satisfaction it gave me was worth it. Several of them even commented on how nice the glasses were. It was actually very endearing. 

The chicest and least expensive are widely available at thrift stores, online, yard sales, you name it. I could’ve gone to Target and called it a day for $10 in disposable plastic garbage. But, nah.
Life is only as special as you make it. 

I say, whenever we can do better, we should. From little kids to your most senior dinner guests, the difference is noted and appreciated. 
Also, effort is attractive. And Im not crazy. 😉 
Salut!

This morning, in a place I’ll keep to myself, I overheard a woman talking to a mutual friend about her grown child’s crisis. From my seat, I was discreet but saw such worry and fear in her face. When she caught my eye and appeared a bit embarrassed, my heart broke. As a mother, I could only imagine her pain and anxiety. I didn’t want her to feel even worse. 

Before I left, I gently approached her. “I know it’s hard, but it will get better,” I said, sharing a story from a similar experience in my family. We both got emotional, and her gratitude was clear as she smiled and thanked me for approaching her. In that moment, I realized it wasn’t just about giving her hope for her child, but a reminder of a simple yet profound truth: grace often arrives unannounced, in moments of vulnerability. It can change a day, a situation, even a life. And as my friend said goodbye to me, he hugged me a little tighter than usual. I realized then that grace had touched us all, leaving us a little more connected, and perhaps a little more hopeful than before. Amen.

Have a great day.
.

So, here we are at Christmas. It’s a time painted in the warm glow of festivities-parties, the excitement of gifts. These are the hallmarks of the season, the ‘good stuff’ we eagerly anticipate.

Yet, amidst that merriment, Christmas can also be a mirror reflecting a spectrum of emotions. It’s a period when the air, echoed with cheer, might also carry the weight of solitude, sorrow, or longing. The season’s brightness can often cast shadows on memories of loss, unspoken yearnings, or heartaches held close, shared only with the silence of our pillows at night. Whitney Hanson, in her poignant words, described it as a checkpoint – a moment in time where life’s realities might contrast with our hopes and expectations. Her insight reminds us that it’s okay if our lives don’t mirror the festive ideal, if we find ourselves craving more comfort, peace, or a sense of stillness. It’s a shared human experience, and in acknowledging this, we realize we are not alone in our feelings.

I’m fortunate to not experience chronic depression, but like many, I’ve navigated through these varied emotions. While I’m no expert in human behavior, I’ve found that on my tougher days, the way out often lies in extending kindness to others. It could be a warm smile, a generous tip, an unexpected gesture of goodwill, or a simple message to someone saying, “I’m thinking of you.”

In my world, where I often guide you towards the latest must-haves or the next big thing to purchase, I’ve come to learn that the most profound gift we can offer is our love and compassion. That, in its essence, is the true spirit of Christmas.

With this in mind, I extend my heartfelt wishes to you. May love, peace, and joy find you not just today, but every day. May we all spread the real treasures of Christmas – kindness, understanding, and human connection.

I have nothing but love and gratitude for all of you. Merry Christmas, lovely people. ❤️

Recently, I've had a few conversations about the importance of details  with friends, particularly in personal style. These details, I believe, are what elevate the ordinary to the extraordinary, whether it's in an outfit, a living space, or the presentation of a meal. It's about adding a touch of the special to everyday life.

For instance, when my son began fifth grade, he wore a shirt and tie daily. I had his initials embroidered on his shirt cuffs. It was around $40 for five shirts but looked so different.
A little goes a long way.

At just 11 years old, he noticed the difference. So did the dry cleaner and his teacher, to name a few. It was a small gesture, but it demonstrated a willingness to go that extra step. It may seem insignificant, but consistently adding these touches makes everything feel a little nicer. Whether it’s this or fresh flowers or making a sandwich or a drink look pretty-even if just for yourself, why not make it a little more special. Who wouldn't want more of that in their life? 
Hope your Monday was fantastic. XO
